[ConsumerApp bootstrap]
│
├─ parse config (`AppConfig.fromEnvAndArgs`, env keys like CONSUME_QUEUES, DEAD_LETTER_QUEUE, consumer backoff/retry values)
├─ create virtual-thread executor (`newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor`)
├─ create `ConcurrencyLimiter` (max in-flight, acquire timeout, rate limit)
├─ init `HttpUpstreamClient` (timeout, circuit breaker 50% failures, 5s slow threshold)
└─ instantiate `RabbitMqConsumerTask`, register shutdown hook, and `start()` it

[RabbitMqConsumerTask.runLoop]
│
└─ for each queue in `consumeQueues`:
     ├─ `basicGet(queue, autoAck=false)` until empty
     ├─ for each delivery:
     │     ├─ ensure limiter permit (otherwise `basicNack` + requeue)
     │     ├─ `forwardToHttp`: rebuild method/path, send via upstream client (circuit breaker around HTTP/timeout)
     │     │     ├─ success (2xx) → `basicAck`
     │     │     └─ failure / exception → `retryOrDeadLetter`
     │     └─ catch exceptions → log + `retryOrDeadLetter`
     │
     └─ if no deliveries, sleep `consumerPollIntervalMs`

[retryOrDeadLetter]
│
├─ read `retryCount` header (default 0) → increment
├─ if `nextRetry <= consumerMaxRetries`:
│     ├─ sleep `consumerBaseBackoffMs * 2^(retryCount-1)` (capped by `consumerMaxBackoffMs`)
│     ├─ publish back to original queue with updated `retryCount`
│     └─ `basicAck` original message
└─ else:
      ├─ publish to `deadLetterQueue` (same headers/body)
      └─ `basicAck` original

[circuit breaker / HTTP path]
│
├─ every upstream call executed via Resilience4j CB with:
│     ├─ `minimumNumberOfCalls=10`
│     ├─ `failureRateThreshold=50%`
│     ├─ `slowCallDurationThreshold=5s`, `slowCallRateThreshold=80%`
│     ├─ `waitDurationInOpenState=30s`, `permittedNumberOfCallsInHalfOpenState=5`
│
└─ failures/timeouts increment CB metrics and trigger retries when the loop hears the exception

[Operational notes]
- Channel reconnect via `ensureChannel()` with automatic recovery and `basicQos(prefetch)`
- Rate/concurrency limits keep HTTP requests bounded even during retries
- Shutdown hook closes consumer and executor

